=== Sample project ===

First create the project:

{{Cmd|django-admin startproject myProject}}

To start development server navigate to the project directory and run:

{{Cmd|python manage.py runserver}}

It will use port <code>8000</code> by default; the port can be changed by adding a chosen port number after the run server command above. Do not use this server for production! It should only be used for development.

=== Apache modules ===

When planning on using Apache for production emerge the [http://wsgi.readthedocs.org/en/latest/ WSGI] (Web Server Gateway Interface) module:

{{Emerge|www-apache/mod_wsgi}}

Enable the WSGI module in Apache's configuration file:

{{FileBox|filename=/etc/conf.d/apache2|title=Enabling the WSGI module|lang=bash|1=
APACHE2_OPTS="... -D WSGI"
}}

Example to set up a given virtual host with WSGI:
{{FileBox|filename=/etc/apache2/vhosts.d/00_myProject.conf|title=Enabling the WSGI module|lang=bash|1=
<VirtualHost *:80>
   ...
   WSGIScriptAlias / /var/www/myProject/myProject/myProject.py
   ...
</VirtualHost>
}}
IMPORTANT: For some funny reason the default wsgi.py file (what you should have renamed to myProject.py, if you follow the example) created by:
{{Cmd|django-admin startproject myProject}}
is not properly set up to work with Apache or other severs expect for Django's own. To fix it you must add this line in your wsgi.py file:
{{FileBox|filename=/var/www/myProject/myProject/myProject.py|Add your project to Python's sys.path|lang=bash|1=
...
sys.path.append('/var/www/myProject') #This is the missing line it must be before os.environ.setdefault(...)
...
}}

